font-weight:bold;font-size:18.0000pt;mso-font-kerning:0.0000pt;" ><font face="SimSun" >3.3 ER diagram</font></span></b><b><span style="mso-spacerun:'yes';font-family:SimSun;font-weight:bold;
font-size:18.0000pt;mso-font-kerning:0.0000pt;" ><o:p></o:p></span></b></h2><p class=p  style="mso-pagination:widow-orphan;mso-line-height-alt:12pt;" ><span style="mso-spacerun:'yes';font-family:'Times New Roman';mso-fareast-font-family:SimSun;
color:rgb(0,0,0);font-size:14.0000pt;mso-font-kerning:0.0000pt;" >The ER Diagram is crucial for designing the relational database. It visually defines the core entities of the Laravel application—such as Users, Products, Categories, Orders, Cart, and Reviews—and illustrates the cardinal relationships between them (e.g., One User has Many Orders; One Order has Many OrderItems).</span><span style="mso-spacerun:'yes';font-family:Calibri;mso-fareast-font-family:SimSun;
mso-bidi-font-family:'Times New Roman';font-size:12.0000pt;mso-font-kerning:0.0000pt;" ><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=MsoNormal  align=center  style="margin-top:18.0000pt;margin-right:0.0000pt;margin-bottom:18.0000pt;
